echo '<div class="mk-prose">';
echo '<p class="mk-muted" style="margin-top:0;">The pogroms against the Igbo — the mass killings of 1966 and their place in the history of ethnic violence.</p>';
echo '<h2>What Happened</h2>';
echo '<p>Between May and October 1966, Igbo people living in northern Nigeria were subjected to a series of mass killings — organized, sustained, and largely unpunished. Estimates of the dead range from 10,000 to 100,000 people. Over a million Igbo fled south. These events — the 1966 pogroms — are the immediate cause of the Biafran declaration of independence and the civil war that followed.</p>';
echo '<p>The pogroms unfolded in stages. The first wave followed the January 15 coup and targeted Igbo officers and soldiers. The second and more devastating wave followed the July 29 counter-coup, spreading from military barracks into civilian populations across the north. Igbo traders, civil servants, students, and workers who had lived in northern cities for decades were hunted, killed, and their properties destroyed.</p>';
echo '<h2>The Word "Pogrom"</h2>';
echo '<p>The word "pogrom" (Russian: "to wreak havoc") originally described organized massacres of Jews in the Russian Empire. Its application to the 1966 killings is deliberate and precise: the violence against Igbo in northern Nigeria was organized, targeted a specific ethnic group, and was accompanied by official indifference or complicity — the defining features of a pogrom.</p>';
echo '<h2>Recognition and Memory</h2>';
echo '<p>The 1966 pogroms remain inadequately recognized in Nigerian official history. No trials have been held. No reparations paid. No formal apology issued. For the Igbo, the pogroms are the foundational trauma of the post-independence era — the event that proved the Nigerian state could not protect its Igbo citizens and made Biafra inevitable.</p>';
echo '<h2>Historical Parallels</h2>';
echo '<p>The 1966 pogroms have been compared to other 20th-century ethnic massacres: the Armenian genocide (1915), the Holocaust (1941–1945), the Rwandan genocide (1994). In each case, an ethnic group was targeted for mass violence by organized forces operating within or alongside a state, preceded by years of organized dehumanization, and followed by international indifference.</p>';
